This cobbled-together flying piece of scrap metal looks as if it should fall apart under a gentle breeze. And yet, it barrels through the air with wild abandon; bullets, bombs and stranger projectiles flying from it in all directions. A mighty flying fortress, this super-scrap bomber all but ignores incoming fire as it passes harmlessly through open superstructure, or as it blasts away rusty plating that was all but falling off anyway, leaving critical structures safe below layers of bolted on scrap metal.

This 67 piece multi-part kit comes with a huge range of options. It can be built with two wing profiles, alternative hulls with differing tailfins, and a range of options for turrets and bombs, many of which can be mirrored for additional variety / symmetry. It includes monstrous 'bouncing bombs' for some truly 'wild' bombing runs!

The kit is designed to be scaled to 8mm scale model games, such as plane warfare games, or those featuring legions of models fighting. It could also be used in 6mm games where Epic Marines fight in Space, a real armageddon level battle. Compatable with ork style armies, it would be a great proxy for a mega bommber or landa. It is sufficiently detailed that an ambitious hobbyist could print it at 400% scale to create a huge center piece model or terrain for 32mm games set in grim dark universes. This would of course require additional cuts to the model!

I am a hobbyist 3D modeller - not a professional 3D designed. However, this project has taken many, many hours of development, test printing and correction. It is my first 'paid for' model, a reflection of the time it took to create. Almost all my other models are currently available for free, so please do look through those if you are interested in further supporting me and my hobby.

The Krumpin' Mega Bot is a hulking, heavily armored monster! Pistons, welded to powerful close combat weapons, such as the Ripper Klaw deliver enormous hydraulik power to every git or vehicle gettin' to close.
Other than the more commonly Deff Bots and or Kans, Krumpin' Mega Bots are usually armed with high speed rattling weapons of high calibers to kill enemies even before reaching them in close combat! (Or just to make horrible loud noise...)

EDIT: Most Parts are compatible to my Skrappin' Mega Bot
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/skrappin-mega-bot
Build your Bot as you like! :-)

FOR BEST QUALITY PRINT, PLEASE READ ALL(!) OF BELOW:

This is my ambitious model until now!

To print this monster, you need time or a resin printer ;-)
I REALLY recommend a layer high of 0.075 or better for all parts to get the quality I intended, while designing this model - please see the pics, those are printed in FDM

(<=0,075mm)!

I tried to keep the need of tree supports low, but I highly recommend it to use tree supports - make sure to set the tree support z-distance to a multiple of 2 for optimal removal

(keep in mind: layer hight 0.05 to 0.075(!) )

For the Rippa Klaw I added a resin version with "_Resin" in the file name - unlike the FDM versions those don't have a flat bottom. (I have not test printed these files, but they

should be good to go!)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
---------- EXCEPTIONAL 'fings for this model: ----------
----------------------------------------------------------------------


---------- GUN ARM: ----------

THE RATTLA KANNON MAGAZINE IS ROTATABLE IF DONE AS INTENDED!!

For the axies you simply insert usual filament!
If you don't glue the "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_06.stl" to "...05.stl" the "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag.stl" is interchangeable - who knows what might be released in future...... ;-)
-> If you don't want this or don't have filament, just glue the parts as wanted.


Assembly as followed: (please see also the last two pics/screenshots!

1. Stick (NOT glue, if you want it to be removable) together:
"MegaBot_RattlerKannon_05" & "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_06", OPTIONAL: "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Barrel.stl"

2. Insert a 1.75mm filament (42mm long - as the answer to all questions, lol) into "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back_Spacer.stl", large side first, followed by

"MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag".

2.a) Glue on all parts of "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back.stl", if you want more realistic details (even if Ork xD).
2.a.note: Warning: print "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back.stl" with "brim" 3mm+.
They will, regardless of brim width, fall apart after removing the brim. This is intended so you can glue them bitz more random on the Mag!

3. "Dry fit" (NO glue at first!) all parts

3.a) View the last two pics (Tinkercad screenshots)!

3.b) "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Trigger.stl" to
 "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back_Spacer.stl"

3.c) I recommend to glue in "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_TriggerPin.stl" to "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Trigger.stl" first.

3.d) Glue the filament between "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Trigger.stl" & "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back_Spacer.stl"


---------- MAIN BODY ----------

You CAN use two 10x4mm Neodym magnets for the junction "hip <> main hull" to get a rotatable/removable body!

---------- LEGS ----------

The legs are unique, there is a individual model for right / left leg. Those are mirrorable / interchangeable.

---------- Over all printing recommendation! ----------

Many parts have a "flat surface" - face those to the build plate.

Rigged version of an ork made by VidovicArts. I used this to create all my ork models so far.

There are a some hidden parts in the file and lots of poses in the pose library of the rig. My workflow with this is as follows:

-Add objects like torsi an weapons to the file an pot them to the right place at the body
-hide all parts you don't need for your boi
-make copy of the rig, the body and all parts you added
-parent all objects to the rig (as objects to specific bones)
-choose a pose from the pose library or create a new one.
-apply all modifiers to the parts
-unparent all objects while keeping their transformation
-boolean unite all objects
-use windows 3D builder to repair any problems in the mesh
-print

Rigged version of an ork made by VidovicArts. I used this to create all my ork models so far.

There are a some hidden parts in the file and lots of poses in the pose library of the rig. My workflow with this is as follows:

-Add objects like torsi an weapons to the file an pot them to the right place at the body
-hide all parts you don't need for your boi
-make copy of the rig, the body and all parts you added
-parent all objects to the rig (as objects to specific bones)
-choose a pose from the pose library or create a new one.
-apply all modifiers to the parts
-unparent all objects while keeping their transformation
-boolean unite all objects
-use windows 3D builder to repair any problems in the mesh
-print

This is inspired by the original Kev Adams 1990's era gargant with the rounded belly and arm and shoulder weapons.

some of the notable changes I made to the original design was the placement of the feed, rather than underneath they are to either side of the body, Another change was how I mounted the Buzz saw, I wanted it to look like it had a greater range of movement the 3d change was to the belly gun mount the original left huge holes in the belly that could be seen through during games, so I have added a big mantlet that I think gives the gargant a more solid look.

Also a minor tweak i widened the balcony on the back so now you can add infantry models there, but if you intend to do this do it before gluing the top body to the mid body.
With the modificatiosn its a little wider than the old model, and best mounted on a games workshop 80mm or reaper miniatures 75mm base. I have included a simple printable base id you don't have either of these sizes to hand

theoreticly you could scale this up for Titanicus, you would need to print at about 150%, priniting full size for 40k may be 2 difficult unless you cut up the hull parts or happen to have a huge print bed
